# Deep Covering Options for Long-Horizon Web Agent Training

> **Research Note** — Transferring spectral graph-based option discovery to GUI agent agentic training on GUI-360° and AndroidWorld benchmarks.

---

## 1. Core Physical Intuition

### 1.1 The Resistor Network Analogy

The state space of an RL agent can be understood as a **resistor network**:

- Each state is a node; reachability between states is a wire.
- The second smallest eigenvalue of the graph Laplacian, $\lambda_2$ (algebraic connectivity), corresponds to the network's **equivalent conductance** — how freely a random walk flows across the entire network.
- The **second eigenvector** $f$ assigns a "voltage" to each node. The pair of nodes with the maximum and minimum $f$ values are the two endpoints of the **highest equivalent resistance** — the bottleneck where information/flow is hardest to transmit.

**Adding an option = wiring a shortcut across the bottleneck.** This shortcut directly bridges the highest-resistance endpoints, maximally boosting global conductance.

### 1.2 Why This Solves Long-Horizon Problems

Long-horizon training fails because the path from start to goal is a **long series of resistors** in series. The equivalent resistance is enormous, so the gradient signal (the "current") is effectively zero by the time it propagates back to early decisions.

$$\text{Long chain: } R_{\text{total}} = R_1 + R_2 + \cdots + R_{25} \quad \Rightarrow \quad \text{signal } \approx 0$$

Inserting shortcuts (macros) at bottleneck points converts serial segments into shorter sub-chains:

$$\text{With macros: } R_{\text{effective}} = R_{\text{seg1}} + R_{\text{seg2}} + R_{\text{seg3}} + R_{\text{seg4}} \quad \ll \quad R_{\text{total}}$$

Each macro's internal policy is pre-trained (low internal resistance), so the high-level planner operates on a much shorter effective horizon.

### 1.3 Iterative Bottleneck Elimination

After adding one shortcut, the original bottleneck is relieved and $\lambda_2$ increases. Recomputing $f$ reveals the **next bottleneck** (the new weakest link). Adding another shortcut there further tightens the graph. This iterative process transforms a "long chain" topology into a "tight cluster" topology, step by step.

| Layer | Physical Analogy | Algorithmic Counterpart |
|-------|-----------------|------------------------|
| Global structure | Equivalent conductance of the network | $\lambda_2$ (upper bound on cover time) |
| Bottleneck identification | Node pair with maximum equivalent resistance | $\arg\max f$ and $\arg\min f$ |
| Bottleneck repair | Wiring a new conductor | Generating an option connecting the two ends |

**Key insight: we find "hard-to-reach" places in connectivity space, not Euclidean space.** Two UI states may be spatially close on screen but functionally distant if they require many precise intermediate steps to transition between.

