## 6. Positioning Against Existing Methods

### 6.1 Comparison with Current SOTA Approaches

| Method | How It Handles Long-Horizon | Weakness |
|--------|---------------------------|----------|
| Reward shaping | Hand-designed intermediate rewards | Task-specific, labor-intensive |
| Hindsight relabeling | Relabel failed trajectories as successes for sub-goals | Hard to define "partial success" in web tasks |
| Curriculum learning | Train on short tasks first, gradually increase length | Requires task difficulty ordering |
| Hierarchical reflection (Minitap, MobileUse) | Retry and reflect after errors at inference time | Token-expensive; fixes symptoms not causes |
| GRPO / trajectory-level RL (Step-GUI, MobileRL) | End-to-end RL with trajectory rewards | Still suffers from long credit assignment chain |
| **Covering options (ours)** | **Auto-find bottlenecks, build shortcuts at training time** | **Task-agnostic, no reward signal needed** |

### 6.2 Complementarity with Inference-Time Methods

Minitap (100% on AndroidWorld) uses multi-agent + hierarchical reflection + post-validation — it fixes errors **after** they happen through retry.

Our approach reduces errors **before** they happen by shortening the effective horizon. The two are **complementary**:

```
Covering options:  shorten horizon → fewer opportunities for errors
    +
Reflection/retry:  catch and fix the remaining rare errors
    =
Multiplicative improvement in success rate
```

